Here are the main performance bottlenecks, ranked by impact:

---

## 1. Nginx configuration (highest impact, no code changes)

This is the most likely cause of slow page transitions. The static `out/` directory needs proper Nginx config:

```nginx
# Enable gzip compression
gzip on;
gzip_types text/html text/css application/javascript application/json image/svg+xml;
gzip_min_length 1024;

# Cache _next/static/ forever (content-hashed filenames)
location /_next/static/ {
    add_header Cache-Control "public, max-age=31536000, immutable";
}

# Cache other assets
location ~* \.(webp|png|jpg|svg|woff2)$ {
    add_header Cache-Control "public, max-age=86400";
}
```

Also enable **HTTP/2** in Nginx — it multiplexes the many small JS chunks Next.js generates.

Without gzip, the uncompressed JS bundles (React + Next.js runtime + mermaid + KaTeX + syntax highlighter) can easily be 3–5MB transferred.

---

## 2. Mermaid is eagerly loaded on every post page

`mermaid` is ~1.5MB minified and is statically imported in `MarkdownRenderer.tsx:2` via `Mermaid.tsx:4`. This inflates every post's JS bundle, even posts with no diagrams.

It should use `next/dynamic`:

```ts
// MarkdownRenderer.tsx
const Mermaid = dynamic(() => import('@/components/Mermaid'), { ssr: false });
```

---

## 3. KaTeX CSS loaded globally

`app/layout.tsx:13` imports KaTeX CSS on every page (~280KB unminified). It should only load on posts with `latex: true` — move it into the post page layout, conditionally.

---

## 4. react-syntax-highlighter bundle

`CodeBlock.tsx` eagerly imports 17 language grammars. Consider switching to [`shiki`](https://shiki.style/) which runs at build time (zero client-side JS for syntax highlighting) or use the lighter `react-syntax-highlighter/dist/cjs/light` build.

---

**Bottom line**: Fix Nginx compression + cache headers first — that alone will likely make the biggest visible difference. Then address the Mermaid lazy loading.

